snippet.textDisplay:
Get out from under Renault, stop putting JATCO CVT transmissions in everything they make, and go back to quality first mentality like Toyota. Sports cars are only a small percentage of total sales Nissan makes, so it makes sense to focus on cars people can afford that are on par with the quality that Toyota and Honda produce. For God's sake, stop making cars in Mexico where every car manufacturer has suffered from poor quality issues once they started production there. It may look good on paper now, but it'll bite them in the ass later and further degrade their image as a company. Quality, quality, quality even if it means they have to raise the price of their vehicles overall to stay in business. Lastly, do marketing campaigns around quality and innovation which they can demonstrate with short infomercials about how they're improving quality and getting back to the roots they once had as a company.

All of this can only happen by separating themselves Renault which is a piss poor company with shoddy quality control who's losing money by the buttloads.

snippet.textDisplay: Look, I really love you boys at Donut, but “cool” cars are not going to save Nissan.  Fixing the transmissions and rebuilding their reputation for reliability will save Nissan.   Halo cars may get people to an auto show or a showroom, but practical, dependable cars are what get put into the driveways and garages of the vast majority of car buyers... would a new Pro-4X Armada with a locking differential and a disconnecting sway bar be awesome?  Yes.  Yes it would.  But what would sell and save the company is offering a reliable transmission in the Altima, and every other car they make.

snippet.textDisplay: Hold up - let's talk economics for a minute.  Nissan is still shooting themselves in the foot with their pricing. The GTR is just stupid at any price over 80k because it can't compete with a Corvette and only holds about 20% of its value on the used market, and once you start spending new Corvette money on used cars, you may as well start looking at Porsche and Ferrari; the GTR is just ridiculous.  The 370 or 400z needs to be a $40k car where it'll compete nicely with the Civic Type-R until Nissan proves they can build a vehicle as nice as a Toyota or Honda, holds value like a Toyota or Honda, and lasts as long as a Toyota or Honda.  Because in the end, they're still just a Nissan.  If you want to charge what the big boys charge, you have to make the product just as good.
